Denote by $z$ the complex number $a+bi$. We have $(a+bi)(c+di) = (ac-bd) + (ad+bc)i = \frac{7}{16}i\,.$ Thus, $ac-bd = 0$ and $ac = \frac{7}{16}$ so $c^2 = \frac{7}{16}\,.$ Let $R$ be the square region defined by \begin{align*}
R = \{x+yi: -1 \le x \le1, -1 \le y \le1\}
\end{align*}and let $U$ and $V$ be the subregion such that $\frac{7}{16}i = (x-c) + (y-d)i$ for $(x+yi)\in U\cap V\subset R$. If we parameterize the sides of $R$ by $x$ and $y$, we have \begin{align*}
\frac{7}{16}i = \begin{cases}(x-1) + (y+1)i &\text{and}& 1\le x\le\frac{7}{16}, \; -\frac{9}{16}\le y\le 0\\(x+1) + (y-1)i &\text{and}& -\frac{9}{16}\le x\le -1, \; 0\le y\le\frac{9}{16}\\(x+1) + (y+1)i &\text{and}& -1\le x\le\frac{9}{16}, \; -\frac{9}{16}\le y\le 0\\(x-1) + (y-1)i &\text{and}& \frac{9}{16}\le x\le 1, \; -\frac{9}{16}\le y\le 0\end{cases}\\
\end{align*}which simplifies to \begin{align*}
\frac{7}{16}i = (x-c) + (y-d)i = (-x-d) + (y-c)i \Leftrightarrow x = \pm\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}, \, y = \mp\frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\end{align*}We get four nice and easy to check circles each with area $\frac{\pi}2\,.$ <answer><math>\frac{\pi}{2}\cdot\frac{\pi}{2} = \boxed{\frac{\pi^2}{4}}\,.$</answer>

